question: Pick a set of figures from history for your own special dinner party where you get to talk to them.
answer:
I believe your special dinner party should have the following guests: Napoleon Bonaparte, Abraham Lincoln, Indira Gandhi. Here's why:

Lincoln's administration saw some of the bloodiest battles fought on the home front. Although Emancipation was achieved during his Presidency, he struggled with the management of the economy in relation to that change. It would not only be interesting but informative to discuss this with him.

Napoleon's dramatic rise to power from humble beginnings is both inspiring and paradoxical, especially when you consider his eventual heavy handed rule and restrictive policies: in effect prosecuting his own revolution.

Ghandi's leadership style has been highly influential in social change around the world, informing movements towards civil rights and proper government. His perspective on moral imperatives to address social ills would be valuable at such a gathering.

Martin Luther King, Jr.'s massive, non-violent protest movement for equality and civil rights could benefit from a discussion with these historical figures. They would provide course corrective feedback becoming essential to achieving Mr. King's goals.

question: Pick a set of figures from history for your own special dinner party where you get to talk to them.
answer:
Alan Turing J.R.R. Tolkien Marie Curie Amelia Earhart Martin Luther King, Jr. In my imagination I can hear what they would say, and I will transcribe that here. Alan Turing: "Cryptographer mislead my enemy, allow me to act. For six years work was done, humanity's survival to win wars. Here's what I learned: Daring and deluding, cryptographer gets result." J.R.R. Tolkien: "I was Tolkien then. I told tales of heroic wars. A world called 'Middle-Earth,' where hate couldn't be banished but power mixed with empathy and love could take over. I learned:'Destruction of the Ring' shows transformation of hate into wisdom and grace." Marie Curie: "Dashing into unknown brought us unseen wonders. Revealing secret wonders unloads thirst for knowledge. I learned: Unseen wonders transformed all life. History's chain reaction of progress." Amelia Earhart: "Flew over mountains and oceans, exploring edge of Earth's winds. Seeing world from above ignited determination to pierce boundaries. I learned: Wide view of world ignites the spark to bridge boundaries." Martin Luther King, Jr.: "We dreamt of a better tomorrow and fought for our worth. Met obstacle with steadfast spirit, bending unyielding nature's course. I learned: Hope and change caused storms but inspired progress." These are the voices and perspectives we heard, guests at my dinner party. Excerpts of their words show how they've influenced the world's trajectory. answer:

    Presume I already hate democracy.

question: Pick a set of figures from history for your own special dinner party where you get to talk to them.
answer:
I'd choose the following four guests: Frida Kahlo: Mexican painter known for self-portraits and paintings of flowers with underlying meanings: brush and color choice indicate emotion, natural forms often contrast with manmade shapes, juxtaposed symbols of life and death, iconic images layered with autobiographical details. Georgia O'Keeffe: 20th century visual artist who painted enlarged flowers, skulls, landscapes of natural beauty, depicting American Southwest in many works. Mina Stone: Greek sculptor, painter, ceramicist; founder in 1968 of the first feminist artist workshop in Greece. Featured in the International Arts Movement; her work in public, private, and museum collections world-wide. Sonia Delaunay: Known for vibrant, abstractly designed patterned fabrics, wall hangings, prints, tennis scores, and books she covered; the first artist to apply abstract art to everyday objects in design. This dream dinner party would likely be a celebration of colors, bold and bright paintings, career accomplishments, gypsy jazz-influenced calm atmosphere and no eye-roll at excessive creativity allowed!
